# /etc/udev/rules.d/70-uinput-solaar.rules — installed by chezmoi
# (system/linux/etc/**, .chezmoiscripts/30-linux/install-system-10-files).
#
# Grant the ACTIVE SEAT USER write access to /dev/uinput so Solaar's rule
# engine can synthesize input under Wayland: the MX Master gesture rules in
# ~/.config/solaar/rules.yaml use KeyPress (Super+Left/Right window tiling on
# GNOME) and MouseScroll (thumb-wheel horizontal scroll), and under Wayland
# both write through evdev uinput — "For uinput to work the user must have
# write access for /dev/uinput" (logitech_receiver/diversion.py). Stock
# Ubuntu/Fedora grant no user access to the node. TAG+="uaccess" has
# systemd-logind maintain a per-session ACL for the active seat user —
# granted on login, revoked on seat change — instead of a permanent
# group/mode widening.
#
# ORDERING: the filename number MUST stay < 73 — the uaccess tag is
# processed by systemd's /usr/lib/udev/rules.d/73-seat-late.rules, and a tag
# added by a later-sorting rule is never seen. OPTIONS+="static_node=uinput"
# makes udevd apply this rule to the static /dev/uinput node at daemon
# startup, before any device event / module load.
#
# NOTE: the installer only reloads the rules database (`udevadm control
# --reload`, deliberately no `udevadm trigger`), so on the FIRST install the
# ACL lands at next boot. To grant it to the current session immediately:
#   sudo setfacl -m "u:${USER}:rw" /dev/uinput
# (the same command diversion.py's own header documents).
KERNEL=="uinput", SUBSYSTEM=="misc", OPTIONS+="static_node=uinput", TAG+="uaccess"
